The mean pulmonic gradient for the Ross procedure was 18.0 mmHg (95% CI: 16 to 
20, P<0.0001) at latest follow-up. The evidence for all outcomes from 
observational studies was deemed to be of very low quality, while the evidence 
from RCTs was downgraded for imprecision and moderately serious risk of bias.
CONCLUSIONS: Compared to conventional AVR, the Ross procedure was associated 
with better aortic valve hemodynamics. Future studies should evaluate the impact 
of the Ross procedure on exercise capacity and quality of life.

